{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real filesystem watching behavior: the behavior text says a file is \"placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root\" and must be detected/processed. Recursive watch support and emitted events are OS/watcher-backend dependent, so in-process mocks can hide real failures.","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temp directory tree, create a nested subdirectory, write a file into it, and assert exactly one transformed output is produced for that nested file path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior targets local decision logic (\"deduplication logic\" + \"same file path within a configurable time window\"). A single dedup component test with controlled time/path inputs can catch the real failure without OS/network/subprocess. Rejected higher levels: no behavior text requiring real filesystem events or cross-process effects.","test_description":"Call dedup policy/function twice with the same path under a fake/controlled clock and configured window; assert first request is accepted and second is rejected, then accepted again after window expiry.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly names OS event behavior (\"operating system emits multiple filesystem events\"). Mocked emitters can miss real duplicate-event patterns from kernel/watch backend; minimum boundary is real OS/filesystem watcher interaction.","test_description":"Run daemon on a real watched directory, perform a single write pattern known to trigger multiple fs events (e.g., temp-write+rename or chunked write), and assert only one pipeline execution/output for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This depends on real filesystem lifecycle events (delete/recreate) while process is live. Failure appears at OS watcher boundary and re-subscription behavior; in-process fakes often do not reproduce backend watcher invalidation/recovery semantics.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real temp directory, remove watched directory, recreate it at same path, then add a new file and verify it is processed without restarting the daemon.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.92,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior binds ordering to real file arrival plus filesystem timestamp metadata (\"arrive at the same time\" and \"creation timestamps\"). Real OS timestamp resolution/event interleaving can cause failures that mocked arrivals may hide.","test_description":"With daemon running on a real directory, create multiple files nearly simultaneously with controlled creation-time ordering, then assert processing/output order matches observed creation timestamps.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.76,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a real filesystem timing/atomicity condition (arrival event before write completion). Whether partial files are visible and when close/rename events fire is OS/filesystem dependent; mocks can falsely pass by simplifying write timing.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real directory, begin a slow/chunked write to a file, verify no processing occurs mid-write, then complete/close the file and assert processing starts only after completion.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.89,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
